WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.540
So, I have been asked to talk about this CADENCE304 study, a randomized study between BGB16673

00:00:08.540 --> 00:00:13.980
versus Piltobutynib in relapsed refractory CLR trial that started in October last year,

00:00:13.980 --> 00:00:16.680
has not been completed yet and not been reported yet.

00:00:16.680 --> 00:00:19.960
So, from that perspective, the talk will be short.

00:00:19.960 --> 00:00:25.720
To my surprise, the talk will be even shorter because Dr. Ereda did an exceptional introductory

00:00:25.720 --> 00:00:31.400
talk and actually with more updated data covered a lot of what I plan to say.

00:00:31.400 --> 00:00:39.380
So, this trial is a battle between a degrader versus the latest inhibitor and Piltobutynib

00:00:39.380 --> 00:00:46.120
is a non-covalent inhibitor that is designed to get past the equivalent inhibitor mutations.

00:00:46.120 --> 00:00:53.200
However, it has its own set of problems with inhibitors that confer resistance to Piltobutynib

00:00:53.200 --> 00:00:54.400
and BGB.

00:00:54.400 --> 00:00:55.700
The degraders are designed to...

00:00:55.700 --> 00:01:02.200
...to get past that, yet there are mutations that confer cross-resistance to both.

00:01:02.200 --> 00:01:09.200
So, BGB16673, I think we don't have to introduce it because Dr. Ereda just did that.

00:01:09.200 --> 00:01:12.520
Interestingly, it's also seen as penetrating.

00:01:12.520 --> 00:01:20.360
It degrades both wild-type and mutant, and it is not affected by many of the covalent

00:01:20.360 --> 00:01:24.700
and non-covalent BDK inhibitor mutations.

00:01:24.700 --> 00:01:25.680
These are earlier data.

00:01:25.680 --> 00:01:33.340
The actual data from ASH24, you saw the ASH25 data from Dr. Ereda, earlier responses across

00:01:33.340 --> 00:01:43.320
different time points, dose points for the Phase 1 study showing excellent response even

00:01:43.320 --> 00:01:47.240
at very light, small doses.

00:01:47.240 --> 00:01:54.680
You saw the updated progression-to-survival curves by Dr. Ereda, overall response rate

00:01:54.680 --> 00:01:55.660
94%.

00:01:55.660 --> 00:02:00.480
So, there was a good start of the battle.

00:02:00.480 --> 00:02:07.660
Interestingly, the inhibitor was really not affected by many of the BDK mutations listed,

00:02:07.660 --> 00:02:13.180
as well as many other mutations that confer resistance and high-risk features in CLR.

00:02:13.180 --> 00:02:19.580
So, that was a very promising finding in this Phase 1 study.

00:02:19.580 --> 00:02:24.760
The Phase 1 study also included the Victor's transformation, and there were some patients

00:02:24.760 --> 00:02:25.640
that...

00:02:25.640 --> 00:02:35.180
12 patients were, at the time of that presentation, efficacy-available, and they were heavily pre-treated.

00:02:35.180 --> 00:02:40.240
All patients had received a prior covalent BDK inhibitor, and overall response rate was

00:02:40.240 --> 00:02:41.240
58.3%.

00:02:41.240 --> 00:02:44.240
CR rate was 8.3%, so very low.

00:02:44.240 --> 00:02:50.740
But five of the seven patients that had a response remained on treatment for at least six months,

00:02:50.740 --> 00:02:54.440
so not exactly what you would expect for Victor's transformation.

00:02:54.440 --> 00:02:55.520
I think that's a good start.

00:02:55.520 --> 00:02:59.160
You should think about combinations with a compound like that.

00:02:59.160 --> 00:03:04.580
So, of course, there has not been any head-to-head comparisons, but if you just look at the phase

00:03:04.580 --> 00:03:10.020
of it, what is known from the Phase 1 data of the BGB compound, the pivotal trial for

00:03:10.020 --> 00:03:16.180
Pitobutinib and a randomized study against standoff care, all these trials include very

00:03:16.180 --> 00:03:23.220
heavily pre-treated patients with prior BDK inhibitor exposure and high-risk biologies

00:03:23.220 --> 00:03:25.400
with deletion 17 and p3-femutase.

